In this article, the author discusses the meeting between the President and the family of George Floyd, emphasizing that George Floyd should still be alive today. The author acknowledges that the guilty verdict in the trial of Derek Chauvin provided some justice, but it does not solve the persistent issue of police misconduct and excessive force. The pain of the Floyd family and other families who have lost loved ones in similar circumstances remains. The author highlights the need for more action, mentioning the Justice in Policing Act introduced by Senator Cory Booker, Representative Karen Bass, and themselves to hold law enforcement accountable and build trust with communities. The author urges Congress to act quickly and with a sense of urgency to pass this legislation, acknowledging that it won't bring back the lives lost but will represent progress. They also emphasize the importance of addressing racial injustice wherever it exists.